---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import Sidenote from '../components/Sidenote.astro';
import HoverCard from '../components/HoverCard.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Paul Diaz Ashot"
	description="Founder-operator. Founding team at GMX. Active Claude developer. London, Barcelona, New York."
>
	<main class="essay">
		<div class="essay-content">
			<header class="essay-header">
				<h1>Paul Diaz Ashot</h1>
				<div class="locations">London, Barcelona, New York</div>
				<div class="contact">
					<a href="mailto:paul.ashot@icloud.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">paul.ashot@icloud.com</a> ·
					(646) 996 5037 ·
					@supersonicsines
				</div>
				<div class="work-auth">Right to work: UK, US, EU. Native English, fluent Russian, fluent Spanish.</div>
			</header>

			<p class="lede">
				I'm a founder-operator. The short version of my work is two seasons: four
				years on the founding team of <HoverCard term="GMX">
					<span class="hc-p">A decentralised perpetual exchange. Built originally as Gambit on Binance Smart Chain, then re-architected to Arbitrum and Avalanche as GMX. Three-person founding team, no outside investment, $450M+ TVL and $40M+ in annualised fee revenue at peak.</span>
					<span class="hc-p"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — replace with 200–300 word essay covering: the GLP unified-liquidity-pool design, your specific role in growth/partnerships, the Arbitrum migration, the deal arithmetic that made it work. Include TVL screenshot.]</em></span>
					<span class="hc-p further-reading">→ <a href="https://gmx.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">gmx.io</a> · <a href="https://defillama.com/protocol/gmx" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DeFiLlama TVL chart</a></span>
				</HoverCard>, then three years of independent AI deployments. The PDF version of
				this CV is the index; this page is the network it points at.
			</p>

			<Section title="Now" id="now">
				<p>
					I'm currently running three things in parallel. The first is <HoverCard term="Pawlymarket">
						<span class="hc-p">A live scraper and statistical-arbitrage layer over prediction markets. Reads order books across Kalshi, Polymarket, and a handful of smaller venues; identifies systematic mispricings; surfaces them as actionable calls to a small subscriber base.</span>
						<span class="hc-p"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — replace with 150 words on the engineering architecture (scrape-aggregator, statistical model layer, P&amp;L attribution), revenue trajectory, and lessons learned. Embed dashboard screenshot.]</em></span>
						<span class="hc-p further-reading">→ <a href="https://pawlymarket.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">pawlymarket.com</a></span>
					</HoverCard>, a prediction-market analytics platform that's been live and
					revenue-generating for the past year. The second is a <Sidenote id="vinted" term="Vinted-to-Depop reselling agent"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> An end-to-end autonomous fashion-arbitrage agent operating across Vinted and Depop. Driven by Claude through a Telegram interface; sources items, calculates margins, lists, fulfills.</Sidenote> that runs end-to-end through a Telegram interface. The third is an <Sidenote id="booking" term="intelligent booking system"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> Claude-powered scheduler for a small local business. Takes class bookings, reschedules around capacity, and organises future classes from predicted demand.</Sidenote> for a small local business.
				</p>

				<p>
					Two utility tools run in the background: a Claude-based <Sidenote id="inventory" term="inventory automation"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> Backend pipelines that keep listings, stock, and pricing synchronised across marketplaces without human review. The unsexy half of e-commerce that, when working, is invisible.</Sidenote> pipeline that keeps cross-marketplace listings synchronised, and an <Sidenote id="email" term="email triage"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> A Claude-based classifier that drafts replies, escalates urgent threads, and snoozes the rest. Built it for myself; would happily ship it as a product.</Sidenote> system that drafts replies and escalates urgent threads. Both started as personal pain points and turned into running systems.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="GMX" id="gmx">
				<p>
					From late 2020 to early 2023 I was on the founding team at GMX — a
					decentralised perpetual exchange that grew, with three people and no
					outside investment, into one of the highest-revenue DeFi protocols of its
					era. We started on Binance Smart Chain as Gambit, re-architected to
					Arbitrum and Avalanche as GMX, and at peak ran $450M+ TVL and $40M+ in
					annualised fee revenue.
				</p>

				<p>
					My role was growth and partnerships. I closed and co-closed strategic
					integrations with <Sidenote id="chainlink" term="Chainlink"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Chainlink BUILD programme integration gave us oracle pricing for the entire perpetuals book. Negotiated the grant component and the keeper-network configuration with Chainlink Labs.</Sidenote>, <Sidenote id="avalanche" term="Avalanche"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Avalanche Rush deployment incentive was one of the largest external capital injections into GMX, and the cross-chain expansion onto Avalanche roughly doubled our TVL within two months.</Sidenote>, and <Sidenote id="frax" term="Frax"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The Frax integration brought frxETH liquidity into GLP and gave us a stablecoin alternative to USDC. Co-designed the parameters with the Frax core team over a couple of weeks of technical back-and-forth.</Sidenote>, plus three smaller protocol integrations along the way. I co-led the <HoverCard term="Gambit → GMX rebrand">
						<span class="hc-p">The rebrand wasn't a marketing exercise; it was a chain migration. Binance Smart Chain to Arbitrum, Gambit to GMX, with the partner network lined up to launch alongside.</span>
						<span class="hc-p"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — replace with 150–200 word account: why the rebrand was technically necessary, your specific contribution to the partner outreach, the timeline coordination across Chainlink/Avalanche/Frax. Include rebrand announcement link.]</em></span>
					</HoverCard> and the chain migration that came with it.
				</p>

				<p>
					Across three years I sourced $20M+ in cumulative professional liquidity to
					the protocol. I built and ran the institutional and community channels —
					five thousand Telegram members and direct relationships with eight-figure
					liquidity providers. I exited at a <Sidenote id="exit" term="seven-figure number">Crystallised proportionally to my equity. The dryness of this footnote is intentional.</Sidenote>; the protocol's numbers from that period are public, the personal arithmetic is less so.
				</p>

				<p>
					Since GMX I've run <em>Portico Ventures</em>, a small advisory practice for
					early-stage DeFi and fintech founders. Three portfolio companies — including
					<a href="https://gammaswap.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Gammaswap</a>
					and <a href="https://www.codex.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Codex</a> —
					and roughly $4M in influenced fundraising through advisory work and warm
					introductions.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="Before GMX" id="before">
				<p>
					Before GMX I was in <Sidenote id="manchester" term="Manchester"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> BSc Chemistry at the University of Manchester, 2018. The interesting work didn't happen in the lab; it happened in the basement of a friend's house in Fallowfield, where I ran a trading-bot operation arbitraging Steam item markets through several account-pool generations. First time I shipped code that made money while I slept.</Sidenote> reading chemistry. The interesting work didn't happen in the lab; it happened on the side, in a small trading-bot operation that taught me to ship code that runs unattended.
				</p>

				<p>
					The intellectual line that mattered most ran from <HoverCard term="Wittgenstein">
						<span class="hc-p"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — replace with 200 words on the late Wittgenstein and the specific insight (substrate-bound thought) that prefigured the language-model paradigm for you. Include a pull-quote that's specifically yours, not the famous one.]</em></span>
						<span class="hc-quote">"Philosophy is a battle against the bewitchment of our intelligence by means of language."</span>
						<span class="hc-p further-reading">→ <em>Philosophical Investigations</em> · <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/wittgenstein/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SEP entry on Wittgenstein</a></span>
					</HoverCard> through to <Sidenote id="yudkowsky" term="Yudkowsky"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 75 words]</em> The early LessWrong sequences were the first place I encountered serious thinking about cognition as something to be engineered rather than studied. <em>The Sequences</em> in particular set the frame for taking AI seriously a decade before everyone else did.</Sidenote>, by way of the LessWrong sequences. I came to the late Wittgenstein in 2014, and the slow point underneath the famous formulation — that thinking is something we do <em>in</em> language, not <em>before</em> it — turned out a decade later to be almost identical to the insight behind language models.
				</p>

				<p>
					In between Manchester and crypto I spent a year at <em>Effie Perine LTD.</em>,
					a private dealership of Old Master pictures, learning what consultative
					sales of high-ticket items in the £500K to £2.5M range actually look like
					day-to-day.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<Section title="Why Anthropic" id="why">
				<p>
					I want to work at Anthropic for the same reason I came to crypto in 2020:
					there's a small window where a category-defining product gets built by a
					small team, and the work is not yet a commodity. I've spent the last three
					years using Claude in production and treating <Sidenote id="cai" term="Constitutional AI"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The CAI paper and the more recent character-training work. The aesthetic restraint of the approach is the thing that distinguishes Anthropic's outputs from the rest of the field for me.</Sidenote>, the <Sidenote id="interp" term="interpretability"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> The interpretability team's work on superposition, dictionary learning, and feature extraction is, for my money, the most important applied research programme in AI right now.</Sidenote> work, and <Sidenote id="mcp" term="MCP"><em>[PLACEHOLDER — 50 words]</em> MCP changed my development process the day it shipped. The model–tool boundary becoming a clean protocol is the kind of small, correct architectural decision that compounds.</Sidenote> as living documents I keep returning to.
				</p>

				<p>
					What I bring is a founder's instinct for getting product into the hands of
					users who pay for it, attached to a working knowledge of where Claude
					genuinely wins and where the abstractions still leak. I've shipped six
					small production AI deployments in the last eighteen months. The next
					thing I want to do is ship them inside the company that builds the model.
				</p>
			</Section>

			<footer class="essay-footer">
				<a href="mailto:paul.ashot@icloud.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener">paul.ashot@icloud.com</a> ·
				@supersonicsines ·
				<a href="/Paul_Diaz_Ashot_CV.pdf" download target="_blank" rel="noopener">Download CV (PDF)</a> ·
				<a href="/cv" target="_blank" rel="noopener">/cv</a>
			</footer>
		</div>
	</main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.essay {
		max-width: 1000px;
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: 64px 24px;
		position: relative;
		z-index: 1;
		counter-reset: sidenote;
	}

	.essay-content {
		max-width: 680px;
	}

	.essay-header {
		text-align: center;
		padding-bottom: 16px;
		border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--color-rule);
		margin-bottom: 32px;
	}

	.essay-header h1 {
		margin: 0 0 8px 0;
		font-family: var(--font-serif);
		font-size: 36px;
		font-weight: 400;
		letter-spacing: 1px;
	}

	.locations {
		font-size: 16px;
		color: var(--color-ink);
		margin-bottom: 6px;
		letter-spacing: 0.5px;
	}

	.contact {
		font-family: var(--font-sans);
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
		margin-bottom: 4px;
	}

	.contact a {
		color: var(--color-ink);
	}

	.work-auth {
		font-style: italic;
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
	}

	.lede {
		font-size: 18px;
		line-height: 1.65;
		margin: 32px 0 16px 0;
	}

	.essay-content :global(p) {
		font-size: 18px;
		line-height: 1.65;
		margin: 0 0 16px 0;
	}

	.essay-content :global(a) {
		color: var(--color-ink);
		text-decoration: underline;
		text-decoration-color: var(--color-rule);
		text-underline-offset: 2px;
	}

	.essay-content :global(em) {
		font-style: italic;
	}

	.essay-content :global(b) {
		font-weight: 700;
	}

	.essay-footer {
		margin-top: 64px;
		padding-top: 24px;
		border-top: 0.5px solid var(--color-rule);
		text-align: center;
		font-family: var(--font-sans);
		font-size: 13px;
		color: var(--color-muted);
	}

	.essay-footer a {
		color: var(--color-ink);
	}

	@media (max-width: 768px) {
		.essay {
			padding: 40px 20px;
		}

		.essay-content :global(p) {
			font-size: 16px;
		}

		.lede {
			font-size: 16px;
		}
	}
</style>
